{
  "texts": [
    "Whereas knowing what happened elsewhere in the world might have been impossible, or might have required taking others on their word, we can now, in a radically expanded array of cases, know by seeing for ourselves.",
    "This point is epistemically significant, as seeing for oneself-whether literally or in a more inclusive, intellectual sense of \"seeing\"-is highly valued in both folk and academic epistemology (Pritchard, 2016).",
    "Thus, even if it is possible to acquire knowledge through the testimony of others, one is likely to feel some pressure to see for oneself if this option is easily available.",
    "Suppose, for example, that one is curious as to the weather outside.",
    "One can come to know about the weather by either asking one's partnerwho has just returned from outside-or by looking out the window."
  ]
}